Specs.Tip: Although more width gives you more lateral space inside the cabin, it makes the car more difficult to park in narrow spots.
Specs.Description: A car's width is defined as its widest point without its mirrors.

Specs.Tip: Taller the car, the more headroom there is on offer inside the cabin. However, a tall boy stance also affect the car’s centre of gravity which can cause more body roll.
Specs.Description: The height of the car denotes the highest point of the vehicle from the ground.

Specs.Tip: The longer the wheelbase, the more space there is inside the cabin.
Specs.Description: The space between the center of the front and rear wheels.

Specs.Tip: If the car has a good amount of clearance, it’s easier for it to clear big speed breakers and overall, deal with bad roads.
Specs.Description: It’s the space between the lowest point of the car and the ground.

Specs.Tip: A lightweight car will always be more efficient and easier to manoeuvre whereas a heavy car would give you a sense of solidity while driving.
Specs.Description: The total weight of the vehicle with all the standard equipment and all the required fluids.

Specs.Tip: A boot with a large and wide opening is ideal for loading heavy items. Additionally, a lower loading height also makes it easy to put in luggage.
Specs.Description: Boot space defines how practical the car is with respect to how much luggage it can carry.
The number of people that can be seated comfortably in the car, which has also been mandated by the car manufacturer.

Specs.Tip: If a car has a large fuel tank, it can cover long distances without refuelling.
Specs.Description: The official volume of the fuel tank of a car, usually denoted in litres.
The number of doors define the category of car. For example – four door means sedan, two-door means coupe while five-doors usually refer to a hatchback, MPV or an SUV.

This is the maximum fuel efficiency that an engine gives. All numbers are provided by the manufacturer based on tests conducted and specified by the standards of the ARAI (Automotive Research Association of India)

Specs.Tip: A bigger displacement and more than four-cylinders generally indicate a performance-oriented engine.
Specs.Description: The official title given by the manufacturer in terms of the name of the engine, the displacement and the number of cylinders.

Specs.Tip: The higher the capacity, the more the output but it can also affect fuel efficiency. A smaller displacement engine is more environmentally friendly.
Specs.Description: The displacement refers to the total capacity of the engine block and this is measured in cubic centimeters using the bore of the block multiplied by the stroke of the piston.
Maximum power delivered by an engine or motor
Peak torque delivered by an engine or motor
All cars in India either run on petrol, diesel, CNG, LPG or electric power.

Specs.Tip: A manually operated transmission is the most popular type, thanks to its simplicity and low cost. Varied types of automatic transmissions are also available.
Specs.Description: Type of transmission used to transfer power from the engine to the wheels

Specs.Tip: A higher number of gear ratios reduce overall stress on the engine, making it more fuel efficient.
Specs.Description: The number of gears that the transmission mated to the engine has to offer.

Specs.Tip: Front-wheel drive (FWD) is most common in mainstream cars while expensive cars or SUVs come with rear-wheel drive (RWD) or all-wheel drive (AWD).
Specs.Description: Cars come with different drivetrain configurations depending on the segment.

Specs.Tip: ESP or ESC cannot increase traction but rather improve control or help regain control in slippery conditions.
Specs.Description: System designed to improve car stability and control, especially when the car is accelerating.

Specs.Tip: Keyless entry and start/stop (KESS) systems in some cars also include operation via a smartphone.
Specs.Description: When fitted, this system allows the car to be switched on without removing the key from the driver’s pocket or vicinity.

Specs.Tip: Higher the power, the peppier the engine but it can also affect fuel economy.
Specs.Description: Gives a good idea of the performance of the vehicle under full thrust. A higher figure here usually means a higher top speed as well.

Specs.Tip: The more torque at low RPM range makes the engine feel more responsive. It also allows the engine to run smoothly without too many gear changes.
Specs.Description: Relates to in-gear acceleration. A higher figure here means better roll-on acceleration, fewer gear shifts, and possibly better fuel efficiency.

Specs.Tip: ABS is a great accident prevention technology, allowing drivers to steer while braking hard
Specs.Description: An electronic system that prevents the tyres from locking and skidding in emergency braking situations by pulsing the brakes (quickly releasing and reapplying the brakes)
Claimed or CarWale Tested fuel efficiency of a car when driven in the city.
Claimed or CarWale Tested fuel efficiency of a car when driven on the highway.

Specs.Tip: TPMS can prevent dangerous accidents by indicating a loss of pressure immediately. Some systems also provide air temperature information which can be helpful in racing/track driving.
Specs.Description: A digital gauge that provides the live status of the air pressure in every tyre of a car.

Specs.Tip: Turbochargers are more effective but require plenty of heat management. Superchargers, meanwhile, offer linear bump in power but they are comparatively more complex.
Specs.Description: Manufacturers today offer turbochargers to boost engine power without affecting its fuel economy. Superchargers are found in more expensive cars but on the downside, they are not very efficient.
